s="sc-fPrdjK gxzXqc pf-121_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Runner rugs are designed for narrow spaces such as hallways, kitchens, or alongside beds:<br><br>• <em><strong>Width:</strong></em> Typically 2 to 3 feet (61 to 91 cm)<br><br>•&nbsp;<em><strong>Length:</strong></em> Ranges from 6 to 14 feet (183 to 427 cm)<br><br><strong>Tip: </strong>Ensure the runner leaves a few inches of floor visible on each side to create a balanced look.</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-123_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px;position:relative" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-pKreJ bIaXH pf-124_"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-iLLNPL gTJAOY pf-125_">Common Standard Area Rug Sizes Overview</h2></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-127_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px;position:relative" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-pKreJ bIaXH pf-128_"><p class="sc-fPrdjK gxzXqc pf-129_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Need a quick comparison? Here's your go-to chart for standard rug sizes and where they fit best.</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-131_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px;position:relative" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-pKreJ bIaXH pf-132_"><div class="sc-iQbOXA eQIbmu pf-133_ pf-table-basic" data-pf-type="Table"><table class="pf-inner-table"><tbody><tr><th class="A1"><span>Rug Size</span></th><th class="B1"><span>Dimensions (cm)</span></th><th class="C1"><span>Best For</span></th></tr><tr><td class="A2"><span><strong>2x3 ft</strong></span></td><td class="B2"><span>61 x 91 cm</span></td><td class="C2"><span>Entryways, bathrooms, small accent areas</span></td></tr><tr><td class="A3"><span><strong>3x5 ft</strong></span></td><td class="B3"><span>91 x 152 cm</span></td><td class="C3"><span>Small offices, reading corners, bedside rugs</span></td></tr><tr><td class="A4"><span><strong>4x6 ft</strong></span></td><td class="B4"><span>122 x 183 cm</span></td><td class="C4"><span>Under armchairs, in front of doors</span></td></tr><tr><td class="A5"><span><strong>5x7 / 5x8 ft</strong></span></td><td class="B5"><span>152 x 213 / 152 x 244 cm</span></td><td class="C5"><span>Small living rooms, under coffee tables</span></td></tr><tr><td class="A6"><span><strong>6x9 ft</strong></span></td><td class="B6"><span>183 x 274 cm</span></td><td class="C6"><span>Medium living rooms, queen beds (2/3 coverage)</span></td></tr><tr><td class="A7"><span><strong>8x10 ft</strong></span></td><td class="B7"><span>244 x 305 cm</span></td><td class="C7"><span>Large living rooms, queen/king beds (full fit)</span></td></tr><tr><td class="A8"><span><strong>9x12 ft</strong></span></td><td class="B8"><span>274 x 366 cm</span></td><td class="C8"><span>Large dining tables, king beds, open spaces</span></td></tr><tr><td class="A9"><span><strong>12x15 ft</strong></span></td><td class="B9"><span>366 x 457 cm</span></td><td class="C9"><span>Extra-large rooms, open floor plans</span></td></tr></tbody></table></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-134_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px;position:relative" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-pKreJ bIaXH pf-135_"><p class="sc-fPrdjK gxzXqc pf-136_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3"><strong>Tip: </strong>Always measure your space and furniture before choosing a rug to ensure the right fit and visual balance.</p></div></div></div></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-138_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px;position:relative" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-pKreJ bIaXH pf-139_"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-iLLNPL gTJAOY pf-140_ pf-heading-1-h2"><i class="sc-jBeCGk cNfKko pf-141_ pf-icon-1 pfa pfa-star pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide pf-hide" data-pf-type="Icon"></i>When to Consider Custom Rug Sizes</h2></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-142_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px;position:relative" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-pKreJ bIaXH pf-143_"><p class="sc-fPrdjK gxzXqc pf-144_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Standard rug sizes are designed to suit most rooms, but they are not always the perfect solution. Some spaces need a more flexible approach to achieve a balanced and functional look. Here are common situations where a custom or non-standard rug may be worth considering:<br><br><em><strong>•&nbsp;Irregular room shapes: </strong></em>Spaces with alcoves, angled walls, or unconventional layouts often do not pair well with traditional rectangular rugs.<br><br><em><strong>•&nbsp;Open or oversized layouts:</strong></em> In large or open-concept rooms, standard sizes may leave too much floor exposed or fail to define individual zones clearly.<br><br><em><strong>•&nbsp;Non-standard furniture placement: </strong></em>Unique furniture arrangements, such as curved sofas or built-in units, can make standard rug proportions feel off-balance.<br><br><em><strong>•&nbsp;Specific design preferences:</strong></em> Some interiors benefit from rugs in round, oval, or freeform shapes that complement the room's style and soften the lines.<br><br>If none of the available standard sizes work for your space, considering custom dimensions or irregular shapes can be the key to achieving both comfort and visual harmony.<br><br><strong>Tip:</strong> Always start with accurate room and furniture measurements before selecting a rug. This helps avoid common sizing mistakes and ensures a better fit.</p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-146_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px;position:relative" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-pKreJ bIaXH pf-147_"><h2 data-pf-type="Heading2" class="sc-iLLNPL gTJAOY pf-148_ pf-heading-1-h2"><i class="sc-jBeCGk cNfKko pf-149_ pf-icon-1 pfa pfa-star pf-lg-hide pf-md-hide pf-sm-hide pf-hide" data-pf-type="Icon"></i>How to Choose the Right Rug Size for Your Space</h2></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-150_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px;position:relative" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-pKreJ bIaXH pf-151_"><p class="sc-fPrdjK gxzXqc pf-152_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">Finding the perfect rug size is about more than just picking a look you love. The right dimensions can improve traffic flow, highlight key furniture pieces, and bring a room together. Here is a step-by-step guide to help you choose confidently.<br><br><strong><em>•&nbsp;Measure your space:</em></strong> Start by measuring the length and width of your room. Take note of any architectural features or furniture that might affect rug placement.<br><br><em><strong>•&nbsp;Plan your furniture layout:</strong></em> Decide where your furniture will go before choosing a rug. For example, in a living room, determine whether the sofa and chairs will sit fully or partially on the rug. In a bedroom, consider whether the rug will go under the bed or beside it.<br><br><em><strong>•&nbsp;Leave enough border space:</strong></em> A good rule of thumb is to leave 6 to 12 inches of bare floor between the rug and the walls. This creates visual breathing room and prevents the rug from feeling cramped.<br><br><em><strong>•&nbsp;Match the rug shape to the room or furniture:</strong></em> Rectangular rugs suit most living rooms and bedrooms, while round or oval rugs work well under circular tables or in entryways.<br><br><em><strong>•&nbsp;Avoid going too small: </strong></em>One of the most common mistakes is choosing a rug that is too small for the space. A rug that just floats under a coffee table or barely peeks out from under a bed can make the room feel disjointed or unfinished.<br><br><em><strong>•&nbsp;Use painter's tape to outline the size:</strong></em> Tape the rug dimensions on the floor to visualize how it will interact with your furniture and walkways before you buy.<br><br><strong>Tip:</strong> When in doubt, size up. A slightly larger rug will often make a room feel more cohesive and inviting. To explore more size options and find rugs that match a variety of layouts, feel free to browse <a href="https://www.lanyspace.com/collections/shop-all" target="_self"><span style="color: rgb(1, 126, 86);"><u>our selection of curated designs</u></span></a>. </p></div></div></div><div class="sc-hzhKNl fltMam pf-154_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:15px;position:relative" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-sm:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-pKreJ bIaXH pf-155_"><p class="sc-fPrdjK gxzXqc pf-156_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph3">A good rug ties the room together. It adds warmth, defines the space, and makes everything feel more complete. The right size helps your furniture feel settled and your home feel more inviting.<br></p></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div><script>
